sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K315039
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: pBad + RBS + cre + pTet + lox5171 forward + RBS + RFP + loxBri forward
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part consists of cre recombinase behind a weak promoter and a floxed RFP gene after a stronger promoter. This construct can be used to determine how various lox sites recombine and whether cre has different affinities for different lox sites.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Nitya Rao
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part was created in our lab.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Cre recombinase is behind a weaker promoter to prevent the protein from excising all of the RFP genes in the cell. However, RFP is behind a stronger promoter because a minimal level of protein production is needed for it to be a useful reporter.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K315028
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: pTet + lox5171 forward + RBS + RFP + loxBri forward
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This construct consists of a promoter followed by a "floxed" RFP gene. Because the two lox sites are not identical, we do not expect RFP to be excised when cre recombinase is introduced.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Nitya Rao
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: We created this part in an effort to determine how various lox sites interact.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: pTet is a moderately strong promoter. RFP is a readily visible reporter.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: RBS based on Elowitz repressilator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K315001
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: variant forward lox site with 2 base changes in the spacer region (lox5171)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The cre-lox system is used for site-specific recombination. Lox sites are 34 bp sequences of DNA that flank coding sequences. When cre recombinase is introduced, it can excise or invert the portions of DNA between two lox sites. If the two lox sites flanking the coding sequence are both forward or both reverse, the coding sequence will be excised, leaving one lox site behind. If the one site is forward and the other reverse, the coding sequence will be inverted.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Nitya Rao
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: We learned about the use of variant lox sites to produce random fluorescent protein expression from the "Brainbow" paper (http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v450/n7166/full/nature06293.html). We discovered this specific sequence in "Role of nucleotide sequences of loxP spacer region in Cre-mediated recombination" (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9714735).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: In constructing variant lox sites, we looked for the least promiscuous sites - those that had the lowest rates of recombination with other variants.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: p(tetR)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Sequence for pTet inverting regulator driven by the TetR protein.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Lutz, R., Bujard, H., Nucleic Acids Research (1997) 25, 1203-1210.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: BBa_R0040 TetR-Regulated Promoter is based on a cI promoter. It has been modified to include two TetR binding sites and the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: mRFP1
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: **highly** engineered mutant of red fluorescent protein from Discosoma striata (coral)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: monomeric RFP: Red Fluorescent Protein. Excitation peak: 584 nm Emission peak: 607 nm
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Drew Endy
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Campbell et al., PNAS v99 p7877 URL
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
TAATAA double stop codon added (DE).
Four silent mutations made to remove three EcoRI sites and one PstI site: A28G, A76G, A349G, G337A.
